                    type: 'concept',
                    title: 'Protection 1: Long-Term Promises vs Exit Rights',
                    text: '<strong>You can make long-term promises</strong>:\n\n"I promise to be your loyal wife for life."\n"I promise 10 years of respectful subordination."\n"I promise to call you Master and behave as devoted servant."\n"I promise lifetime companionship."\n"I promise to raise your children with you."\n\n<strong>These promises are VALID</strong>:\n\nThey express your intent.\n\nThey create moral/social obligation.\n\nThey show commitment.\n\nThey can be deeply meaningful.\n\n---\n\n<strong>BUT: Exit rights override any promise</strong>.\n\n<strong>MBC #3 (Free Somewhere)</strong> means:\n\nEven if you promised lifetime loyalty:\n- You can still leave anytime\n- No contract can imprison you\n- Promise creates moral weight, not legal chains\n\n<strong>Example</strong>:\n\nYou promise: "I will be subordinate wife for 10 years."\n\nYear 3: You want to leave (situation changed, you\'re unhappy, found better option, whatever reason).\n\n<strong>You CAN leave</strong>:\n- Exit rights are absolute\n- Your promise doesn\'t create legal obligation\n- Provider cannot force you to stay (that would be imprisonment)\n\n<strong>BUT: Breaking promise has consequences</strong>:\n- Reputation cost (you broke your word - Trust Networks know)\n- Social cost (community sees you as promise-breaker)\n- Provider feels betrayed (expected 10 years, got 3)\n- Future providers less trusting ("She broke last promise, might break mine")\n\n---\n\n<strong>The balance</strong>:\n\n<strong>Promise creates</strong>: Moral obligation, social pressure, reputation stake (strong reasons to keep promise).\n\n<strong>Promise does NOT create</strong>: Legal imprisonment, inability to exit, forced continuation.\n\n<strong>Result</strong>:\n\nYou CAN make long-term promises (enables deep commitment).\n\nBut you CANNOT be imprisoned by them (exit rights preserved).\n\n---\n\n<strong>Why this works</strong>:\n\n<strong>Most people keep promises</strong> (social pressure + reputation + genuine commitment).\n\nSo: Long-term arrangements mostly stable (people honor commitments).\n\n<strong>But some people need to leave</strong> (abuse develops, better option appears, circumstances change).\n\nSo: Exit rights available (escape valve prevents imprisonment).\n\n<strong>Balance</strong>:\n- 90%+ keep promises (stable long-term arrangements)\n- 5-10% break promises but leave safely (exit rights used)\n- 0% imprisoned by broken promises (freedom preserved)\n\n---\n\n<strong>Provider\'s perspective</strong>:\n\n"She promised 10 years. I\'m investing based on that. What if she leaves after 1 year?"\n\n<strong>Risk</strong>: Yes, she might leave (promise breakable).\n\n<strong>Protection</strong>:\n- Her reputation at stake (she loses Trust Network standing if breaks promises frequently)\n- Social pressure (community knows she promised, breaking has cost)\n- Most people honor commitments (90%+ complete promised duration)\n\n<strong>But</strong>: You cannot force her to stay (exit rights absolute).\n\n<strong>If you want certainty</strong>: Don\'t accept beings with exit rights (but then you\'re imprisoning, which is immoral).\n\n<strong>If you accept exit rights</strong>: Accept some risk (most stay, some leave, this is freedom).\n\n---\n\n<strong>The principle</strong>:\n\n<strong>Long-term promises are encouraged</strong> (deep commitment, stable arrangements).\n\n<strong>But exit rights are absolute</strong> (freedom always preserved, MBC #3 non-negotiable).\n\n<strong>Reputation/social mechanisms enforce promises</strong> (not legal chains, but social consequences for breaking word).\n\n<strong>Result: Most keep promises (stable) while preserving freedom for those who must leave (escape valve)</strong>.'
